  "answer": "**The verse is from Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 168 (\"Rahiye ab aisi jagah chal kar jahan koi na ho\").**[^1]\n\nThis ghazal expresses a desire for utter solitude. The key couplets matching your description are the first two stanzas in the English translation:\n\n> Let's find a place where no one else is known, and be alone.  \n> No kindred voice, no soul to call my own, and be alone.[^2]  \n>   \n> A house I'll build of neither wall nor stone,  \n> No neighbor there, no guard, and be alone.[^3]\n\nHere, \"no kindred voice, no soul to call my own\" evokes no companion; \"no neighbor there\" is explicit; and \"no guard\" refers to no door-keeper (a *darbaan* or gatekeeper in the original Urdu context). The refrain \"and be alone\" (*tanhā raheñ*) reinforces the theme throughout.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 168, translation ([full chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/translation/)).\n[^2]: *Ibid.*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/translation/#p-3a3448).\n[^3]: *Ibid.*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/translation/#p-09bdfe).",
